\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Widow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 The year when you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 1918. And widowed in 1942. So there you go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Approximate year of birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Approximate year of birth - oh put seventy years ago, seventy-two we'
ll say. Yes. Approximate, I think that covers a multitude.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 The place where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Casterton. Kirby Lonsdale. A very tiny village but very pretty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How long did you live there, in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Eeh I don't know.
 Well about a couple of years wouldn't I to bring it to 1900 when we got here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And you moved to Riddlesden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 In 1900?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 To this particular house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No, no, no, to another, house. Dad was a gardener.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Whereabouts was the other house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
He was a gardener down at West Riddlesden Hall down at the bottom. And it was owned by a solicitor, James Clarkson. His grandson is still - working in the town. Colin Clarkson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was this house where you lived in the grounds of the hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No, it was a cottage. Still there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Near the Hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. Three minutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you know why it was that you moved from Kir}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5060256\charrsid9796337 k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 by Lonsdale to Riddlesden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh the money. And five children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Your father's job brought him to Riddlesden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. Oh yes, the money was better you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You lived at the cottage in Riddlesden for about how long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh dear oh dear oh dear. Until I would be about - we'd live there about ten or eleven years. As near as I can think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was it then that you moved to this house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
And came here. We lived at Barleycote for a few months but - that doesn't matter does it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was that in between?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes, until we got a house here. We were waiting for a vacancy here you see. And we lived in the farmhouse at Barleycote.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Why was it you wanted to move here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - they were supposed in those days to be very - good family houses, which they were you see. And dad had got this job as foremen of the Rural District Council and it was handy for everything, it was handy for the school. That was the reason.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You moved because it was a better house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 In all? Or brought up? To be living all together there were five of us. Two
 brothers older than me you see, mother had had seven children. But five of us lived to grow up. The two brothers older than me and a brother and a sister younger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What was the approximate spacing between the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh two years, that was the fashionable age in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh - oh I don't know, would he be about - would he be about thirty-two or three or four. Perhaps thirty-three - when I was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh Casterton. That was where he was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And he was a gardener, did he do any other jobs either before or after?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Apart from his gardening? Well - he'd go poaching. You'd better shut it off and then I'll tell you a tale. Yes, he - everybody in the vi
llage poached you see, except the parson and the policeman, in Casterton. You see, the River Loon was at the bottom of the wood. And if the bobby saw a man coming out of the wood with a sack on his back, he'd just say, goodnight Jim. Next day he would cal
l
 you see at mother's - to see how the babies were, there was always one in the cradle. And there'd be his little paper parcel on the table. He said nothing, mother said nothing. But he picked up the parcel, and when he got home it was his piece of salmon.
 
That's how they did it in Casterton. And the parson knew. And he used to call to enquire about the babies. And he got tomorrow's dinner. There were great goings on I think in that little village. I wish I lived there. No, that would be the only other job 
he did. Besides his gardening, just his bit of poaching.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did he do any poaching round Riddlesden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no, no, he was respectable. It wasn't the fashion here you see, and it was the fashion in Casterton. That's just it. No, not in Riddlesden. No, he was quite a good citizen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You say he became foreman for the council?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 The Rural District Council you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was this for gardening?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
No, it - the roads - everything like that. It wasn't - supported by the town at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 So what did his duties cover?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well he used to do a lot more than his duties. He would tackle anything. You see. They had steam rollers you see in those days. And if the steam roller came round and - things weren't getting on quite as quickly as James thought - J
ames would buckle in and help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 About when would he become foreman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh he started straight off. About the year do you mean? Oh that was - oh - fifty-eight years, fifty-nine. About fifty-nine years ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 So he really left the gardening at that stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. It was a better job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did he continue with the council for the rest of his working life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. But he died when he was seventy you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 But he worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes, he - until he fell poorly a couple of years before he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did he ever do any casual or part time jobs as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well he had this big garden here you see and his hens. He hadn't time to do anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you remember him ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 About how old would your mother be when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Twenty something. She would be perhaps about five years younger than dad.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh she came from Keistwick. Kirkby Lonsdale was here. There there was the river you see, Casterton was here, and 
Keistwick was here, but you had to come all round Kirkby Lonsdale to go courting. You see, you couldn't jump over the river. See, so mother was born in Keistwick. There was Kirkby Lonsdale and dad, but it was a trek to go courting. Like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did she have any jobs before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 She was a cook. There was only - domestic work you see round about there.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was she with a big household?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Was she with a big household? Yes. She was at Casterton Hall for her last job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 That was before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I think that was when the courting began you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 After she was married did she go out to work at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no, she'd no time. Washing and cooking and sewing for a flock of five. Oh dear no, a full time job and then she 
had to read her books in between you see, just to - just to get a bit of rest, no, mother had no time to go out to work, not to earn money. She would help anybody. But not to earn money. She hadn't the time. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 The first house in Riddlesden would 
be the house you were living in the longest as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. The cottage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How many rooms were there there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
How many rooms, well it was - two cottages joined into one. There was a door knocked between so there would be one room there, one r
oom there. And - two bedrooms to that and a very big bedroom and a smaller one to that. And then there would be - a little passage and - what we called the back pantry. And then a big - place - wash house thing beyond that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 So you had two rooms downstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. It was the two cottages made into one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Two rooms downstairs, your back pantry and your wash house and your four bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were the two downstairs rooms a living room and a kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 A parlour do you mean. There wa
s a living room, now - I suppose - that - the one would have been a sitting room but you see, my eldest brother had been delicate, and he was treated when he was young because he had this - tummy trouble. Well then when he was ten it was diagnosed that - 
h
e had a diseased - vertebrae you see. So he had to lie flat on the mattress, you see, for fifteen months. So what would have been the parlour was made into his room. And as it had a door out into the garden, anybody could come in, without interfering with
 
mother and her jobs they could pop in to see him. 'Cos there was this little lad lying flat on his back without a pillow - and - all we children when we came home from school, if we picked up a peculiar cockroach or anything - would - take it in you see. 
H
e even harnessed cockroaches to a matchbox. Oh - he wasn't dull. You know, he wasn't a helpless invalid. Flat - not to move, but - he harnessed these and he had a cat you see. Oh and he - and - his appetite wasn't good and he'd just give this cat - a litt
l
e bit of his dinner you know. And one day he howled the house down for mother to go - mother, mother, mother. Mother though he must have slipped and went, there was the cat, she'd caught a mouse. And she'd skinned it. And she was giving him what she thoug
h
t was a delicacy - the inside of the mouse. And she was trying to push it down his throat. So that was the parlour of the house you see. What would you call it? Would you call it the wild beast show or - goldfish and such like, an aquarium. Or just simply
 a madhouse?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And the other room was your living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
We lived in the other room, yes. And it was an outside necessarium you see. And you went on the cinder path to it. Now if you wanted to go in the dark you had to take a storm lamp. And it was
 a two holer. So it was quite all right, you didn't have to go alone. That' isn't going on is it? Oh cross that - you must nip that little bit out of the tape. But - oh it was quite an event when you had to go to the necessarium. I think it was me eldest 
brother who christened it that, he said it was the word the Ancient Romans used. Hence the word nessy was derived. Have you ever heard of that? Well that's what he said, he'd read it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters live i
n the cottage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Nobody, there was no room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
No. I doubt if she could afford it. - We all had our jobs you see to do, that was why - we had to clean the cutlery and the shoes on Saturday mornings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Did you do that all the time you were at school, or after you'd left school as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
No, I would be off to Kirkby Lonsdale after I left school you see. No, it would be whilst we were schoolchildren. Isaac, my eldest brother, the invalid you 
see, he wasn't an invalid after, he mended up beautifully because he went out to Nigeria, but - he - he didn't do it of course because he had this spell in bed. And - I didn't have to do a great deal of it because he hadn't to use his eyes with being flat
 in bed, so every Saturday morning the Boys Own paper used to come. And I had it to to read from A to Z. Suited me very nicely.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 But the other children had to do their shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes, yes, they'd to get down to the shoe cleaning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was the washing done at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. It was. You know, in one of those boilers that you had a little fire underneath it. And my brother Jack had to light the boiler fire. You see. But he had to be certain that the water was in it first, or the thing would have cra
cked. He had that to light before he went to school. And woe betide him if he forgot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your mother or father mend or make the family clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh mother made all our clothes. And knitted the boys stockings. You see, she would get the short pie
ces from her sisters, you see, just enough to make Frances a frock, you see, so it was sent along and - mother made really some very pretty dresses. And she made the boys trousers, she might start making a pair of trousers when - they'd gone upstairs to b
e
d and the trousers were ready to put on next morning. So - yes, she made the clothes. And as I told you, dad had this - he wasn't going to pay for the boys shoes soling, so he bought a last and you could buy the - leather cut out you see and he soled thei
r shoes for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 But the shoes would be bought in the first place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh - oh yes, yes. He - no, he wouldn't make them. Only repair them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Where did you go to to buy any clothes that weren't actually made for you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well you had to go into 
Keighley. And it was an awfully long way because when we were little - a tram used to come to the Victoria Park, and you had to walk so far. It was a long way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And would you buy shoes in Keighley as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 When did you have new clothes, did you have them for special occasions?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh - well you see, when it was new shoes - you didn't get a new pair of shoes id it wasn't your week. You see. You had to wait, no matter what state they were in. Well you'd been kicking stones. They wouldn't
 have been like that. Well they let water in mother. Well you should have behaved yourselves. It's so and so's turn. So - that was just it, so you learned to take care of your clothes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You were newly turned out for the church anniversary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh fo
r the anniversary. Weather permitting. But mother was one for keeping us - warm you see. And if it was - a blustery day with this new white dress on we had to put a coat on the top. But the moment we had turned the corner away from home - the coat came of
f. Had you any brothers or sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house, cleaning, cooking, washing up and suchlike?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
He was awfully good mind - if - as we got older mother wanted to go to town say with me or anythin
g. Dad was very very good, just leave him some tea ready, he'd have the kettle and he'd have his tea and he'd have the cups on the table ready for us getting home. And every Sunday dinner time of course he washed up, because mother retired behind the book
. See? I don't know what she read but she read, and she was absolutely lost.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 So he washed up after she'd cooked the dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
After she had cooked, he used to wash up and do as he said square up. That was just it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about making the fires or decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh - dad lit the fire every morning. You see, when he got up. And he'd probably have a good fire going by the time - mind you that was at five o'clock. Have a good fire by the time mother got down. And - what was the other thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no, no, mother decorated, she loved it. Oh she - loved it, oh - if she could - just get some paper you know and a bit of whitewash and - oh - she loved it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about repairs to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Repairs to the house? Do you mean di
d dad do them? Well, he was a bit ham handed with a hammer. He was much better with a spade you see. And mother was very very do-it-yourself. You see. I'm not. My nails all go in crooked. Mother's went in straight. So - repairs now - dad would do what was
 necessary. Under pressure. You see. Under pressure. And then as the boys got older you see - they took - just take a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Did he do anything for you as children like dressing or undressing or bathing you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh - he would have done anything. Any mo
rtal thing we'd asked him. He would have - when we were tiny he always took us out. And as I tell you he went to church every Sunday morning and in due time shepherded five children in. And - he would have laid his soul open for us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did he read to you or tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
No, we had to read to him. Because he liked to close his yes you see. And I think it was a little bit of mental laziness. He said he had a bad eye. Well I think he'd had a shooting accident when he was young, but - he could see
 to fire a gun. He could have hit a pigeon on the top of one of those houses so I think he could have read the newspaper couldn't he, if he'd wanted. But he liked to have it read and then he could listen with his eyes closed. So - we didn't mind sitting a
nd reading it 'cos we weren't having to do other jobs see. Oh craft was our second nature.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did he take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh if we said we wanted to go for a walk, and if dad didn't think there were - you see, the roads were more lonely
 in those days than they are today, he didn't think it was nice for us to go up the road or round the fields or here and there and everywhere He'd say, right, come on me lass. I'll go. So that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did he look after you while your mother went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - mother wasn't a person who ever did go out by herself when we were little. She had far more pleasure in sitting down for two or three hours with a book than going out to see a friend. Which now when I look back I think was all wrong. But tha
t was her idea of resting. She wouldn't go and have a good gossip with a friend. So - if she'd wanted to go out dad would cheerfully have looked after us. But you see she never did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did the older children help the younger ones with things they found d
ifficult, dressing or eating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
I was the middle one of the five. Well probably I had to help my sister. I don't think anybody would help us with the eating. If you couldn't eat well you jolly well do without it. No, I don't think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you have to look after the younger ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well the odd occasions that dad and mother used to go out to tea perhaps on Sundays which - might only be two or three times a year - she would leave what we were going to have for tea you see, and - the two older boys 
would supervise. And - we'd have tea and - oh we'd blunder along very nicely and - it was glorious you know just to be on our own. We wouldn't have liked it if it had been - been a habit would we.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did the younger children help the older ones in any way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well now do younger children ever help older ones? No. The parents - well, the mother's pamper the young ones. My sister could have got away with murder. Where I had this to do and that to do, ironing and one thing and another, she never had. She
 was the youngest. See you don't know with being the only one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh definitely, seven o'clock. Mother couldn't have done with us downstairs. I don't say we went to sleep because 
we never did, I tell you we had the candle - reading. But - if she didn't get us off to bed at seven o'clock she had no evening. See? So up we had to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was it she who put you to bed when you were very small, or your father?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh dad would probab
ly go up with us. You know, carry the baby up style of the thing. Mother would get it washed. Whatever sex it happened to be. And - it's nightie on, 'cos everybody - boys wore nighties in those days. And - dad would probably carry the baby up to bed. Oh w
e have had a house haven't we.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How old would you be when you started putting yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Probably when I'd got into trouble. That's just it - off you go up those stairs this minute. And you knew jolly well that - if you didn't get up those s
tairs that should come across your bottom. Oh. You went to bed very quickly, and you were in between the sheets in no time. Oh dear, no, you didn't know my mother. As my brother said, she'd the hand like the kick of a cow. Oh, poor mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you share the bedroom or the bed with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 My sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What were the sleeping arrangements of the family at the cottage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh - well the boys - dad and mother had a bedroom, and my sister and I had. And the boys had a very big one with two beds in it you see. And - that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you have a bedroom spare then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes, we had - the smaller one next to this very big one you see, but as all our relatives lived up at Kirkby Lonsdale and Casterton - when - our aunts came - there\rquote d to be a d
ouble shuffle and - the fry had to go into the smaller one and - leave the better bedroom for the sisters you see. You see. Oh yes, yes, you just had to shuffle about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What room did you bath in?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 My dear, the bath would be in front of the fire. 
You see. And - well - I can remember that whichever me sister of I - we joined at the water, well if we - which was the dirtiest got in last. You see, the cleanest was in first and - I think the lads would have some more water. Perhaps if we weren't dirty
 
one of the lads would have to get in with another panful of - water to heat it up. Well that was it you know. Then you had your supper, your milk or whatever it happened to be, ours generally was milk, and gingerbread, that was nearly always the supper, y
ou had that sat in your nightie at the fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 About how often would you have a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - it depends upon the condition, and what - if it was the school holidays it was nearly a nightly occurrence. You see. But if you were going to school in a c
ircumspect - type of way - well might be lucky if you got it on Saturday. NO - Friday. Saturday very often dad and mother went to town you see. And the grate was one of those with ribs across. We used to love them to go to town on Saturdays, because Isaac
,
 my elder brother, he'd got over his spinal trouble then you see, he used to say, when dad and mother go we'll make some toffee. And - he'd go into the pantry and get the butter and the sugar and the syrup you know and the little pan and put it on this to
p
 rib and stir, and there we would sit waiting. That toffee never went cold. We ate it when it was pulling you see. And - he would stir it, drop a bit - a little bit of it into a cup of water, as mother had done it you see. Oh, it's cooked. Then it would b
e
 tipped onto a - a greased tin. It never went hard. We were supposed to be in bed. Now one night - dad came back. They'd forgotten something. And there were we children eating this hot toffee. Oh bairns, he said, if your mother had to see you, he said, yo
u
'd never sit down for a week. He said, get up those stairs, he says, and don't breathe a word. And he wouldn't you know. Oh he wouldn't - he wouldn't say a word about it. But - that's what used to happen on Saturday nights. Oh it was a gala. It really was
 because - dad and mother had to walk all on the canal bank you know to Victoria Park. Well it was a long trek. But - Isaac used to make the toffee. Of course it didn't enter our heads that mother would miss the butter, sugar and syrup. She -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And she never said anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Never a word you know. Diplomatic to the very last. She would miss it wouldn't she? She would know how much butter she had in the dish. But we thought we were being real devils. Oh I had a very good childhood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Would the same thing apply to having clean clothes as would apply to bathing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
There again it depends upon the condition, and the weather during the holidays and all the rest of it you see. Vests. Well I think you did try to make a vest do for a week. But pants and 
things - well - and it would depend upon the colour of them. If they were dark coloured well you see they would last a few days. But if you were going all pretty in summer weather with a little bit of - frilling at the bottom of them well you couldn't wea
r
 them more than a day because they looked grubby. And that was one thing about mother, she wouldn't have a girl with a - bit of grubby frilling showing, you see. It all depended. Upon the weather - and what sort of clothing you were wearing as to how to o
ften it was changed. If you've missed a lot you know with not being poor. You've probably had more of this world's goods, but - there's an awful lot to be said for family life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Where did you used to have your meals in the cottage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh we had to ha
ve them in this living room, which was the bathroom - on - on the night you see. And it was the table in the middle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were there every any occasions when you ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 As a great treat if - if Isaac was - a bit downhearted or anything 
you see, we'd take the tea into his room and have it in there. That was when he had his spinal trouble. And - only if we were poorly and we had it upstairs. If one of us got say measles, mother used to put the lot into bed. Yes, and let them all get it. B
u
t Jack never would. He'd get into bed but he never measled, he never whooping coughed or chicken poxed, anything. He couldn't take an infectious disease. I'm very glad really because - he was killed in 1916. Well he was only twenty-three so - if he'd been
 
pestered with childish ailments - it wouldn't have been fair. Would it? So he had a lovely childhood. But mother used to put him in with the measles or whatever it was it happened to be and - he never took a thing. I could take anything. Didn't matter wha
t
. Measles, German Measles, didn't matter. But - then - mother would light a - fire up in this being bedroom you see. If one of us had a thing and then we could all go and play with the infected child. And if you got it well you were - you got it and got r
id of it whilst you were still - she said, I might as well have the lot down as one, and have it going on all the summer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You had the cooking range in the living/kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 It was the only thing. There was no gas you see. There were lamps. That's w
hy you'd to have the storm lamp when you went on the little cinder path.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I know your father got up very early but what was the normal breakfast time?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well you see mother used to get up with dad to make his breakfast, well she would have hers. We
ll our breakfast time would be before we went to school. She would put the porridge on, she might sort of get it ready the night before you see. We always started with porridge, which was a very good foundation really for growing children. I mean it - fun
d
s wouldn't have gone to bacon and things like that. Would they? And - are we going on too long, have you got enough tape left? No, we'd have this porridge and then something else. Oh we loved it. If the bread had run out the day before because mother used
 
to make scones in a big iron frying pan you know I expect now they would call them girdle scones, but we'd have these hot scones for our breakfast. We loved the bread to run out. Oh they were hot and they were oozing with butter. Oh it was good. Then we c
o
uld abandon the porridge you see and have a real good sound breakfast. But - when we got older you see, when we got into this house and the boys started work - well they had - they were in Spencer and Clarksons, solicitor's office, and they had to be at n
i
ne you see. Well they'd have to have their breakfast by eight. So - with mother getting dad's and her own - it was a sort of - long continued breakfast. Then when I started work you see I had to be working at eight, well my breakfast was about seven and m
y
 sister's. So mother really needed a cup of tea when it got to nine o'clock, but she picked up her book you see while she had this tea. And if it was very interesting - she forgot to put it down 'til nearly eleven. I expect id did her good. I expect it wo
uld.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Then it would be your dinner time, your next meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh - are we at school now or are we working? Oh yes, well we'll leave school at twelve o'clock you see and go home for our dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What sort of a meal would your mother have prepared?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh - always a very good one. Liver in those days was about tuppence a pound you see. And we used to live the liver day. Liver and onions with dumplings in. And - roast potatoes because they all went in the oven you hadn't to bother with a pan you see
. And then a rice pudding after that. Well it all went in this fireside oven. She had no pans to wash. You see, oh but the liver and onion days - and one day it would be a meat and potato pie. And the crust would be - oh, an inch thick. Beautiful flaky su
e
ty crust you know. Just crumble - you see the advert of Tuc's biscuits on the television, well that just reminds me of mother's suet crust, when it breaks like that. It always broke like that in your mouth. But there was one thing that rather puzzled me f
o
r many many years. Oh I think I was grown up before I knew the reason. It was a great big pie like that, she had two enamel dishes, one held a quart of milk, that she could make a rice pudding you see and the other held the meat. And one corner always had
 
a cross in it. Now I never knew until I was grown up - that this corner of crust - with the cross on it was dad's. There was more meat in it. Yes, I thought that was really crafty wasn't it. Well that was how she used to do. And do you know, an apple past
y
 would be made in the oven. And - oh you could have a real strip off it if you were hungry. Well - when we got to working were always rather poorly on a baking day, going down to work you see. Oh - and a friend used to say, aren't you very well? No, are y
ou? No, I'm not. I'm troubled with this fullness after meals. And it was sheer gluttony. That was what it was, but - oh we had glorious meals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What sort of a meal was your teatime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well - you didn't have a - you didn't have a high tea after a gre
at big dinner like that did you. You might have - home made jam. Having a garden you see, strawberry jam, oh I used to think strawberry jam was so common. We had such a lot of strawberry jam. We had jam. And a bit of cake, and if we'd been a bit - greedy 
the day before and eaten all the cake well there wasn't any but - jam, mother might make a batch of scones for our tea. We didn't have high teas, things like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Then you had your milk and gingerbread at suppertime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What did
 you have to drink for the other meals during the day, was it tea or cocoa?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Breakfast time I don't know what we would - do you know, I can't remember. We had water at midday. We'd have tea at teatime. I think it was in my youth that I learnt to like 
weak tea. I can't make a decent cup of tea now. It's always weak. And dad used to like weak tea, and as we grew - got older and I was the only one left at home, he'd say, oh well, mother has the tea, you and I have husband's tea. Watered down you see. And
 - we'd have tea at teatime I think. Yes, and then we'd have this milk to go to bed with, or cocoa. Just depended. Wasn't drinking chocolate you know in those days. It was cocoa. With some sugar in. Yes, that's what we would have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you have any special menus on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh the joint was cooked on Sundays. I - it just depended whatever the joint was you see and - be a very good dinner, and then of course mother - retired. With her book. And left the washing up and suchlike things. And she used t
o make great big teacakes like that, wassers, and - we put some in the oven you know to heat. Not to toast, to he-t, and then split them, fill the middle with butter. Oh she was very generous with the butter. But - no, they were good wholesome meals. But 
w
e always had a good dinner. In fact - it was so seldom that we had what we termed - one of my friends used to have a tea dinner a few times a - a week you see. I never got a tea dinner. Oh it was - it was a real day if there'd - just happened that mother 
w
as busy doing something, and it was a tea dinner. Oh it was marvelous, it was much better than these beautiful pies and - oh, on Boxing Day as we grew older mother always - had the day off. She disappeared behind her book you see. But - before that she'd 
made a great big pie - oh, it would be three or four inches deep. Was a good cook. And if she wanted to read she jolly well did right, didn't she.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 She made all her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 That was at home in the oven?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 In the oven.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And she made her own jam, what about bottling fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes, she bottled everything. Salted kidney beans, pickled the eggs. Everything in the - everything that could be bottled or jam, mother did it. And - she always used to make abou
t forty pounds of marmalade. I make about seven. And it didn't last very long. Her forty pounds you know. But - she did everything like that. Of course she loved doing it you see. She didn't like spit and polish. But - anything with cooking she loved it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did she pickle onions as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. Beetroot. She loathed the smell of beetroot but nevertheless she would do it. And she'd pickle the onions and - red cabbage you see and - anything that grew over the soil or under the soil, she would use.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about making wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well she made nettle beer but she got drunk. Well you see, her - she made this nettle beer and she put - it was when the lads were in their teens. And she put it into these old fashioned stone beer bottles you see, and - Isaac
, he was the eldest, he had a couple of his pals in, I'd better not mention the name because one is a retired bank manager, and - he could remember it if you would just mention the day mother got drunk. And they'd all have a drop of nettle beer, you see, 
a
nd I took the cork off. Isaac said, tip it on the side woman. So woman tipped it on the side, mother said, well I've made it, I ought to have the first lot. So she had the first lot, she had a glass full - the lads were giving her a little drop. No, she s
a
id, I'm entitled to a full one. And she had a tumbler, and she sat on a chair there, the door was wide open, and that woman laughed for a solid hour. And Isaac said, mother, I'll give you my next week in wages if you can walk upstairs. She could not do a 
t
hing. And the more the boys laughed you see - give over laughing at me. I'm perfectly all right. Mother, you're tight. I'm nothing of the sort, that's nettle beer and there's nothing in it. Oh yes, she - she made - and she made elderberry syrup, oh it was
 
beautiful. Now - mother died in 1945. She lived ten years - long - fourteen years longer than dad. And he had picked these elderberries, he was in bed two years so he'd picked them two years, that's sixteen years. And - it was still in the cupboard, a - a
 
bottle of this elderberry syrup. And it was the Christmas of 1945, my sister had come. She said, have I nothing in this house to drink? I says, we haven't, we've tea and suchlike. And a friend called, well he was rather a connoisseur as regards food and w
i
ne, it was in - in his country style of thing. I says, there's mother's elderberry syrup, but I said, nobody has a bad cold so it's no good. We'll try it, says Anne. So we got it out. Arthur said, how long have you had it? So I told him how many years you
 
see. I says, it must be sixteen years. He says, let me taste it first. So he just had a tiny wee drop, he says, don't have a glass of this. He says, it's liqueur, it's too potent. And do you know, she died and never left the recipe. I don't know how she m
ade it. I wish I did because it was most beautiful. It just went down like cream you know, it slithered down.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Had she been making this for a long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh she always used to make it for bad colds. Always, well - if Jack was killed in 1916 - and 
he had it when he was going to work, that was before 1914 - he used to have this elderberry syrup, and in those days - you maybe able to get it now, I don't know - there was some cough mixture, Doctor White's Compot, and he used to get some of this syrup 
a
nd a good spoonful of Doctor White's Compot and fill it up with boiling water. It was a brew. But it cured his colds. Oh mother had made that as long as I can remember, I do wish she'd written it down. She didn't believe in writing recipes. No. She said a
ny fool should be able to carry them in their heads. I must be a fool because I can't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You grew your own vegetables and - fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you ever have to buy any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes, she had - well, you see, brussels sprouts and savoys and suchli
ke things in the winter. You probably had to buy carrots. And things like that you see. But not the other sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about tinned foodstuffs like fruit, vegetables or meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 My dear, there weren't - there wasn't tinned fruit when we were little. 
There might be tinned fruit perhaps about 1913 or something. As a treat a tin of pineapple. But not a collection of tins in the cupboard like we have today. And tinned vegetables - no. No, if you had vegetables you got dried peas you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You had hens didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 We did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was it your father who looked after them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - it just depended you see. Hens are - are unpredictable. They go to bed early if it's a dull day in the winter. You don't find the hen waiting for a recognised teatime. S
o if if was a dull winter's day and dad wasn't home mother would have to go and give them their corn. They had the soft stuff in the morning. And corn in the afternoon. - Well they weren't going to wait for James coming home at five o'clock, they were rea
dy to go to bed and if they went to bed hungry there would be no eggs next morning. So mother would have to go, if she wanted the eggs next morning she'd to jolly well go and feed them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you have any other livestock, pigs or goats or anything?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No. No. No. Nothing. No, as I tell you the boys had their pets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Do you remember seeing your mother have less food or less of a favourite dish so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No. No. She was a very adequate provider. It was generally - who'
s going to scrape this dish out, I don't want to put it away. No - no - sort of self - sacrificing. No. Not mother. No, she always catered very generously. As I tell you with the meat and potato pie - most - you know, the big quantity of meat was in dad's
 corner. But there'd be a beautiful pie with this nice suety crust, and - you really didn't want a terrific amount of meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were you allowed to talk during the mealtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes. Well we couldn't do otherwise you see because mother's - sisters use
d to come quite a bit and Auntie Fanny, the younger one, I had an Aunt Fanny you know, it's a - sort of music hall joke isn't it, well - she was a - a real life person and - oh we worshipped her. But she and dad you know at - a mealtime, well bless my sou
l. It was shuttle cocking across the table. So there was no point in keeping the children quiet. Oh no, no, we weren't subdued in any way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to have a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 W
ell if mother made the dinner she made the dinner. And if you didn't want it jolly well do without. What was the good of - if - if you were poorly that was a different thing, but if we were healthy children - and we turned our nose up at anything, right, 
do without. Well if you were hungry you weren't going to - do without were you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 If you left something uneaten what was the attitude to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well I expect mother would use her - gumption wouldn't she to use a real old Westmorland word, and she'd 
just think, well that child isn't very well. Or else she might think, that one is being a bit too pernickety. Right. If she doesn't want those potatoes she doesn't want pudding. Well if it was a pudding that you liked you see you jolly well ate the potato
es to get the pudding. With five she couldn't afford to pamper them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
If there was something on the table that you wanted such as the salt could you ask someone to pass it to you or did you have to wait for it to be offered?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well the boys might ju
st look across at it - salt coming up. Being older than me the salt would immediately - come up, see. I'm afraid we weren't - what you might call a perfect family. Far from it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a particular and sit in 
a particular way for meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well, we hadn't to do as I'm doing now, and roll about. Mother would have said, no slouching. Is there such a word as slouch? Oh - well she - she would have said, no slouching. So - hold the knife and fork? Well we were ta
ught to hold it in the correct way when we were - children and we never thought of doing anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Could you bring toys or a book to the table at mealtimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh there was never room. There was never room with seven round a table. No.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about leaving the table, when could you leave?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well, it depended what you had to do. And if you wanted to - make an early exit you just said, please may I leave the table, and you were up and off - before you got permission or anything, but you sa
id it. Please may I leave the table, but - but you were finishing as you went out of the door. But you asked. You asked permission. And - that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you always have the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Now funnily enough we did. Mother would be
 there, dad would be there. I would be there. My sister was there. Jack, here, Harry there and Isaac would be there. Funny isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your mother serve the meal or did your father do the carving?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did mother? I think as far as I can remember d
ad did the carving of the joint. There'd only be carving required you see on Sundays. He would carve and she would serve. That's just it. But she always boiled half a stone of potatoes you see. For seven people. Then there might be a bit left to just fry 
up on the Monday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What order were you served in, was there a special order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh the boss first. And then probably it would go round the table, but I can't just remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Where did the younger brothers and sisters sit before they could fe
ed themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
You know I can't remember them not feeding themselves. I can't just remember that. High chairs - no, they wouldn't have high chairs. Oh - used to have a high chair. It was a little chair with four legs and the stool - had - little sock
ets in and the chair was lifted onto the top of it, to put this child to the table. Now I can just remember that. And then the chair would be lifted out and put on the floor to make a seat and somebody could sit on the stool. I don't know where the idea c
ame from Mother's brother probably, he was a joiner.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Did the children come up to the table in the normal fashion at a pretty early age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
I can never remember - except that we were all at the table together. We had a baby who died when he was three, I can faintly remember him - sitting on mother's knee. But that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Mother. Do you mean to talk confidentially? As you were growing up? All our little love troubles were told Auntie Fanhy you see.
 Oh didn't tell mother those. She was our confident. You know, if we had a boyfriend - whom - you see, if you had a boyfriend here when we started work - and he brought you home you knew that he had good intentions. If he brought you home twice, because f
r
om Keighley right up here was a long way, there were no buses. Now the first time might sicken one off. Well you knew that he was no good at all. But if one brought you home twice - you knew that he was thinking seriously. 'Cos he had all the way back to 
walk. Oh you could read them. Oh you wouldn't tell mother about boyfriends. Auntie Fanny. Well of course she just entered into it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Would you tell your mother about your worries when you were a smaller child, did you feel you could confide in her then? Would you perhaps be inclined to confide more in your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - if you'd had a bit of trouble with anybody at school - and you had come off worst and you came home and told mother she just said, well what - if you said, well they hit me. Well wh
y did you let them? It's not a big of good coming home and telling me now. You shouldn't have let them do it, either get out of the way or hit back. It's policy to get out of the way but, she said, if you can't, hit back. It is not a bit of good coming an
d telling me your troubles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was your father easy to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes. Yes, he was very genial. Oh yes, you could tell him anything. Taking things all round we had a very very happy childhood. No money you see. But we didn't miss it, we never had it, we didn't miss it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well mother expected obedience - and truth. I don't know. I don't think they expected anything. They had brought us up to the best of their ability.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were you brou
ght up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in any special ways?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - in a family - there's what you might term brotherly love, and that can cover an awful lot. You see. Both ways, love, hate, love, hate, love, hate. Now, my brother Jack, I
 don't think - ever - said a cross word to me in the whole of his life. I don't think so, I can never remember it. Whatever I did he would make an excuse for it. I expect I could be a little pig at times. But he could always make an excuse for it. Now Isa
ac would - you see, he was older still, and he'd look at things in a different light. You just mind what you're doing, behave yourself. You see. But Jack, no, he'd smooth things. But my sister, well he'd box her ears. You see, you never know in a family.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd be when you grew up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well of course you see - they suffered an awful wallop. You see in 19 - my eldest brother had come back from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Nigeria{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 in 1914. And it was discovered that he had diabetes
. Well in those days there was no insulin because it wasn't - it wasn't discovered until 1923 was it. No. Well there was no insulin when - Isaac got his diabetes. And - it was all - it had to be done by dieting. Well when he came home he went about six st
o
nes and - he was a biggish chap. Well - the war came along you see, the war came along the week after he got home, Jack went into the Army. And - he was wounded in 1915, rather badly in the head. And - however he mended up and went out again. Well Isaac y
o
u see - mother - oh she was marvellous with his diet. Really she was, he had to have this Energen bread and - in those days it was twelve and something a stone, this Energen flour, which was very dear because the other wasn't a shilling. And - she'd make 
h
is bread and she'd - try - she'd make - I can remember her making him - rhubarb and apple pasties, and she'd sweeten them with glycerine, you see. Well he got that he weighed twelve stones. Well in the July of 1916 we got word. That Jack was killed. That 
did it. The - Isaacs twelve\rquote 
s stones just dropped away from him. And he just dropped and dropped and dropped. Well in the October you see - he died. Well that - when you come to think of it, two in three months. It must have been a big wallop to my parents 
mustn't it? It was bad enough to us girls. But - I don't think they expected anything - really of the rest of us. There were just glad they had us. 'Cos the youngest brother had gone into the Army. There were just the two girls at home. So I don't think r
eally they expected a great deal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did they bring you up to consider that certain things were important in life?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh we used to go to church every Sunday - and Sunday school. But whether it was from a religious point, or whether it was - to form th
e habit - I don't know. Things important in life. Well - I don't - I think you sort of grow up - thinking that truth - and a keen sense of humour, which we all had - oh my sister has a marvellous sense of humour, really she has. And we inherited you see f
rom the parents. I don't think they brought us up - thinking that anything would be important. It was a general good family grounding, and it was up to us to make the best of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What did they think about swearing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Swearing? Oh dad could blow hi
s top beautifully when he was annoyed. Beautifully. Well - when Jack was a little tiny boy he might have been three, and he was at Casterton you see, there was a village pub, well of course - things were horsedrawn in those days and he'd hear the - horsem
e
n and whatnot and - he got quite a flow. Mother didn't like it and he was a little pernickety boy, he didn't like dirt. So mother got - I think I told you - this Lifebouy, and a sponge, and she washed his mouth and - I suppose this child spitted and splut
t
ered and - oh, oh, oh, oh. Mother said, it isn't clean yet, Jack, I'll have to go on. She never heard him swear again. Probably he would do but mother never heard him. And she wasn't a swearing woman. Until - her memory went before she died. And she could
 roar it out. But that wasn't mother you see. But - oh dad could. He had a most glorious flow. Polished absolutely polished. If he was annoyed. But in ordinary conversation, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 When grown ups were talking were you children allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Children should be seen and not heard. That was the motto when I was little.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 If you did something your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well you didn't tell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Suppose they found out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well - if one of the others knew and they sai
d, I'll tell mother - if you don't give me one of your sweets I'll tell mother. So you politely gave a sweet you see. Oh there's a code of honour in a family. Oh a great one you see. No, I don't think our misdeeds - came to light very much. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you remember ever being punished for anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Do I remember being punished? I remember my brother Jack with the Vaseline. Vaseline was the family - family ointment you see. Rubbing my poor bottom. He says, mother, why don't you hit with your fingers cl
osed, not open. She'd hit with them open and raised red stripes, and he had to Vaseline my bottom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What had you done to deserve that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well probably deserved it, I can't remember what. But she said bottoms were the safest place, she says you - if you box their ears you could burst the eardrum. If you smacked that she said it was what they were for. So - that was what ma used to do, but -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 She was quite free and easy with this was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well she had five to reprimand. Had she walloped - on
e, if she got her dander up - She might have injured it you see. Whereas if she gave all five a - a bit of a - you know - you didn't get very much. It was just if you were unfortunate and got near to her, as Jack used to say, watch out for the glint in mo
t
her's eye - and then scoot. Oh yes, I can remember having - I can - oh, I can remember having a plait. Two plaits I think I had. And something was - I must have given mother a back answer or something, she got these two plaits, and she flung me into the k
i
tchen. You see, a rare handle. Oh yes. But it's no good saying - a woman with a family of five, that she's never lifted a finger 'cos I don't believe it, do you? I don't believe it. They would burst. Otherwise. Because I don't think that they hit a child 
to punish the child. I think a mother hits a child because she's ready to - explode. That's what I think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your father ever punish any of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Never. If we got to the end of mother's tether, she would - we always called him dad - she w
ould suddenly say, I'll tell your father. Well when she used the word father we knew it was serious. And of course she would tell this table and - he wore a belt you see, he wore braces. He must - he just have been a pessimist mustn't he,; belt and braces
.
 But he always wore his braces and a leather belt, he said it was for his lumbago, and - he'd just get the buckle, I'll give you my belt buckle end. But he never got any further than undoing the buckle and fastening it up again. No, I don't think he could
 have hit anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Would you say you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Do you mean did you sort of copy one or the other? No, I don't think we copied either
. It just simply came naturally, we knew we had to behave ourselves. Then we went out - when we went out into the world to work - you had your idea you know like everybody has today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 When it was your birthday would you have anything special?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh 
we never missed, there always had to be a cake for everybody's birthday. And the birthdays would start January, March, April, Mother's was in May, my sister's in June. Then it was August. For another brother. Then dad would come for November. So we had to
 have all those parties. Hadn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You had a party for every birthday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh everybody had to have a party, if there was only ourselves it was a party you see. We always had to have a cake with a few silver balls on the top.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about having other people in, did you do that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes, loads of our friends could come. They didn't always - sometimes they got bread and jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I meant on birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh on birthday, oh yes, yes, we could have our friends in for our birthdays, yes. And
 Christmases, Boxing Day was an open house. And me father hung his stocking up to the day he died. When - I think my sister was the last to believe in Father Christmas. - And - she didn't believe in him. It's not true. Dad says, well it' a funny thing - h
e never misses filling my stocking and I'm going to hang it up whether it's true or not. And of course we - up to the day he died we always filled his stocking. Well - Christmas Eve, where's my stocking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you have much in the way of presents from on
e to the other amongst the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well, it would just depend how funds were. And then you see we had mother's sisters. They always sent presents. You see, they weren't married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was this for birthdays and Christmas as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. Always. An
d - we might make things you see. Fretwork became fashionable, and the boys would make a little fretwork bracket affair you know, something like that. Nothing that cost a lot of money because we hadn't got it. But - and we always made our parents a little
 present. You see. It would be - just be something - probably cost nothing at all, might be made out of a bit of paper at school. But it was something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How did you spend your Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh there was this glorious tree. That would come up to t
he top and the two Christmases that Isaac was in bed with his spine, it was in his room and of course he got older and - dad and mother decorated the tree while - when we'd all gone up aloft you see, and he could see the - the - he could see the - decorat
i
ng of it you see and of course - people at Casterton, when they knew that he was - tied to the bed like that, sent a whole lot of presents, so it was a marvellous tree that. Well I had a passion - for scent. And - one of my aunts sent a little bottle of p
e
rfume, probably it was sixpence, I don't know, it wouldn't be any more. And do you know, I dropped it on his bed and it broke. And - oh this beautiful scent had gone. Yes, he says, and I'm fainting now forever. But he diddled me once. He'd started collect
ing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5060256\charrsid9796337 mo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
ths. Everything that lad had, he'd a roomful of insects and whatnot and - he said, look, I've got some lovely scent. So I went you know, and got - he said, get your nose to it. He undid the tin lid and - oh I dropped flat. It was ammonia that he was c
uring the moths in. Mother was cross that day. Yes, she was really cross. Because I - I was really laid out. But - no, we had a - we had beautiful Christmases
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I told you I played the violin. Wel
l Isaac - you see - when he was laid on this mattress - it was a straw mattress, it wasn't a - a pliable one as they are today. It had to be hard. Well a friend called, he said, do you know I think you could play the fiddle Isaac. Could I? He says, I've g
o
t one, he said, that I don't want. And he strung it for him you see and brought it and - showed him how to hold it. And that boy got to playing beautifully, all by ear. He couldn't play by music. He did beautifully. And it passed such a lot of lonely hour
s
 on. And - yes, then there would be the melodian. I think Jack used to play the melodian. Oh and got - I once got a prize - the first prize for playing the violin at school. Now then. Talented family. I've given the fiddle away to a boy in a school band. 
Having no further use for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did anyone in the family sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Sing? Dad was a very good tenor singer and we all thought we could do.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you make music together as a family as one of your activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 We didn't sit round the piano style 
of a thing. Because we hadn't a piano. You see. And we had a dog, but when we started to sing the dog did. See? And then the cat would miaouw. Until mother got fed up. She'd just whisk the lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your parents play games with you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Tiddly-winks and things like that, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about outdoor games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
There weren't in those days - if you played cricket you played it with a bit of wood. And the wicket would be bits of wood stuck in the ground. Outdoor games, do you mean races 
and things like that because - every Whitsuntide you see - we'd have a tea in the school on Whit Monday. We'd go into church - I think. No we didn't. We'd go to various points in the village and sing our Whitsuntide hymns that we'd sung in church on the S
u
nday. Then we'd have a tea in school. Then we'd adjoin to East Riddlesden Hall, into the playing field in front of the Hall and we would run our yearly races. You see, and have a beano then until - dusk. Yes, until about dusk or something like that. But -
 what sort of games were you thinking of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Things like cricket and football or children's sort of games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh but - yes, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
I wondered if possibly your father might have played with the boys or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh dear, no, no, no. No, he ne
ver kicked a football in his life. I don't think football would be encouraged. No, because you see there weren't any - football boots. And it would have kicked the toes off the others. And boots were boots. See?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Your mother did a lot of reading, your
 father didn't, he liked you to read to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 He liked us to read to him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your mother read to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. She read the Keighley News from A to Z. Well you see, while she was doing that the kids were washing up. To help you see. Oh you do get crafty when you live in a family, there's no - oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you remember there being a funeral in the family when you were a child?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes, I remember our youngest - child, he died when he was three. And I remember his because we went to the cemeter
y and forgot all the flowers. I didn't know that these flowers - should have gone with the coffin. I was a little girl in a white frock and a little black sailor hat and a black ribbon round the waist and black woollen stockings and - boots I expect. And 
I
 thought, oh those lovely flowers stopping and Willie going in that box. And it was only when we got to the cemetery that mother remembered the flowers weren't in the - hearse. But it wasn't a proper hearse you see. It was a funeral cab with a box in fron
t
. And a baby's coffin was put in this box. But it was the undertaker who should have remembered. But - when; mother got home and saw these beautiful flowers she gave them to a neighbour. She couldn't bear them in the house. So I do remember a funeral. And
 then of course the next one came in 1916. So there was quite a gap then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Was it just the family who would attend the funeral or would other people be there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no. I can't remember about the little boy's. But at Isaac's funeral - I - anybody - anybody who liked him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What was the convention about mourning clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh you had to wear black.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 For about how long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well you were supposed to wear black for a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Children as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. And after Isaac died - I - I think 
- Had I had a - a costume, they were costumes in those days - dyed - black. And oh I hated it. And I hated my - I hate myself in black now. Can't bear it. And - when the spring came I went into coloured clothes and mother was very cross. I had to wear it 
out of respect. Think about your brother you know and this that and the other. And you mourn him. And I just blazed out in a paddy. I said, look - if I have to wear black because I mourn him I shall wear it all my life. I never }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5060256\charrsid9796337 use}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337  it on afterwards. I didn'
t like it. So I didn't wear black when I went to me father's funeral. I wore a light coloured coat.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Were you taken out visiting neighbours and friends and relatives how you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No because you see we had no relatives here. And mother w
asn't a - a person to go neighbouring. It was when we got sort of - in our teens that we went to our friends. But not with mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were you taken shopping as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no, it was too - not unless a new pair of shoes was wanted. It was too far you see. Mother couldn't trail the tribes of Israel all on the canal bank - could she.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You would be taken if you needed something new?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Fitted out with a new pair of shoes. Then we were taken to Keighley you see. And one brother had a squint in his eye and he had to go to the eye and ear hospital in Bradford. So - every now and again it was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5060256\charrsid9796337 re}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
d letter day when he went to Bradford. And mother brought us all a great big humbug, out of the market. They might be about a penny each you know but - oh 
we'd wait for mother coming back, we weren't bothered about the kid with the squint eye. It was the humbug that was the highlight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you go out with your father, just with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 He might just - I'm just going down to see so and so, I'm 
just going down to Ellam Grange to see Norman Driver. Any offers? You see, and one or two would go with him. We knew if went down to Ellam Grange it would be a glass of new milk you know. I don't think it was really to keep him company.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 It was something different for you to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. There was food for the stomach at the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you remember any other outings with your parents, such as Bank Holidays?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Bank Holidays? Well you see, dad - wasn't - a man who would go to the seaside or 
anything. He enjoyed - shooting. And poaching salmon as I've told you, but - once he left Casterton he daren't go poaching. 'Cos he wouldn't have found as kind a bobby. And he had a friend who had an ironmongers shop in Keighley, Robert Pagett. And they u
sed to go every October up to Appleby, shooting. Well of course dad might bring a dozen rabbits. Was rabbits - rabbits, rabbits, rabbits. It's a wonder we didn't burst. A wonder we didn't grow fur. And - then of course I said that we were -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about going away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well as I tell you, our - holidays were spent at Kirkby Lonsdale with our grandmother and the two maiden aunts. We didn't go to the seaside. Because - our parents couldn't have afforded to take five children. And dad would 
have been bored stiff. And mother would have been like a fish out of water. So if mother wanted a day or two with her sisters dad had to cope with the kids, you see, and that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Your mother and father came with you to Kirkby Lonsdale did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no. We two girls were put in the care of the guard, you see. Now the boys were getting bigger - and Isaac one time cycled all the way there, he and a pal. They cycled all the way to Kirkby Lonsdale, they'd got these bikes. And - they just figured 
it out that if they went on their bike they'd have so much more money. I think our aunts must have been very very tolerant people, to put up with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You went pretty regularly did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes. Every summer my sister and I used to go. When we wer
e old enough to do the journey by ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your mother and father ever go for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes, as we got bigger, and we could sort of - cope at home they might go to Kirkby Lonsdale for a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What sort of things did you do while you 
were on holiday, was it just a case of being in a different environment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well, a cousin - from Preston used to go and stay with her grandmother, so we had a meeting but - we never knew which house we were at you know except to sleep. We'd a real beano for four weeks. Real beano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
You've told me a little bit about your Saturday chores in the morning or reading to your brother, how did you spend the rest of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well it depended if you had any hindrances during the morning. Down at the cot
tage you see - you went out of this laundry door, you were supposed to be doing them in the laundry, cleaning the - knives and forks and spoons, and you cleaned them with bath brick in those days. And a damp cloth, and if you hadn't energy to damp the clo
t
h put a bit of spit on. Weren't supposed to do but we did. Now mother went out of the front door one day and she could hear Jack singing at the top of his voice. She thought, where is that little angel? She didn't say angel. But - she went down the garden
 
path and - she looked where the - and there he was, sat on the top of the rigging of the house polishing spoons. And it wasn't a bungalow. But you see, it was - sloping at the back and he'd climbed up there and up these - she daren't shout at him in case 
h
e lost his balance or else he'd have been down and - broken his neck. I expect he'd get what for played with him when he did get down you know but she daren't say - and there he went on polishing spoons. And she lived to be seventy - nine in spite of it a
ll.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you go out playing Saturday afternoons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh we'd probably play or have friends - playing with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And on Sundays you went to church and Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh it filled the day you see. Twice a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you have special clothes for Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes, you had your Sunday clothes. When shoes got a bit shabby they were handed down for weekdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
What about playing games, did your parents think it was in order to play or work on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You could do what the dickens you liked so long as you behaved yourselves.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Your father went to the church too didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 He went to church because he enjoyed it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no, no, she - she must rest. Wasn't a - dad would say, it isn't a rest you want, mother, its' to read your confounded books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What denomination was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh C of E.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
You told me about the Whitsuntide activities, what about Sunday school outings, was there anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well our teacher used to take us on a picnic to Gi
ll Grange every year. We took our own tea and we called at a little tumble down farm and - got a mug of tea there, and I think she paid the ha'penny a mug for these. Sunday school outings. No apart from this field day which we had on Whit Monday we had to
 
join with the Methodists when they had a boat trip you see, going up to Kilderwick. Which was threepence. And you took your own food. We weren't supposed to go but you see as a great concession they would allow the church children to go. And sometimes - I
 think the Womens Help Society, if I remember - that was belonging to the church - ran a trip to Kildwick and we went on a boat. Because I can remember going to the church for this service.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you remember any other social activities organised by the 
church that you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes, yes, we'd have a missionary day and we - kids, I would be perhaps about ten in those days - if a missionary came from - India we'll say, with the - sari's and whatnot you see, we could put them on you see and we 
were parading and she would just - explain - oh and I - I can remember once being adorned in a yellow and I did want to be in a blue and I couldn't have it, had to have this yellow. And - she said - now my little Indian girls don't look as glum as you do.
 
But - oh yes, we used to have beans. And - at church - well, there was the Womens Help Society you see, and we youngsters up to being thirteen - could - and fourteen I think, were little sisters. Now there's no wonder there's all this trouble and strife -
 
in the black countries. Because we used to make, and you can imagine a child of seven and eight, sewing and stitching her hearts blood into blue and red gingham, and gingham in those days was stiff. And that's what we used to do. Sew all the wretched thin
g
s by hand you see, in the vicarage. There's no wonder there's disturbances out there now. Is there? But - oh used to sew those you see and the vicar's wife used to read a book to us whilst we were doing it. And we had a little purple ribbon round out neck
 
with a bronze cross on it, we were little sisters. And about every three or four weeks we could have a play night. Where we got a bit of gingerbread. I think it was a cup of water, I don't think it ever rose to milk. But it was the play night you see, and
 
that was on a - a Monday night I believe it was. Yes, that' was it. Then when we got a bit older would we join the Womens Help Society. We weren't going to join with the mothers. So they had to form a branch of Junior Womens Help Society. And I think - we
r
e a sore trail to the church wardens. I think we were. There were always - now girls, we need a new doormat - 'cos it was a very poor parish you see in those days. Can you do anything. Yes, we'll get up a dance. And the entrance fee you see was sixpence. 
T
hat is if you were helpers. So we knew where to get the prizes from and we knew that the wardens wives would each make a trifle and we knew we could make a bit of profit. We'd make about two pounds you see that night. Well it was a lot of money then. But 
- that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were there any concerts in the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. And we had a marvellous men's society. And - now mother didn't go to church but whatever her children were in - you see you always had to have refreshments, it was the only way you coul
d make a bit of profit. And - you asked your mother for refreshments. Well - mother never never said no. She would always bake something. For everything. Well with five - it meant that she was always giving it. But now when I look back I never know her re
f
use it and say she couldn't afford it. But - they'd have the concerts. Well we youngsters - would have a concert. And the room would be packed, I think the people were very tolerant. They must have been to suffer, 'cos I don't say that - oh now - there wa
s one when I had to sing, and - it was that song, The Harp that once through {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Tara{\*\xmlclose}
's Hall. I got on the platform - and - the pianist was the weekly schoolteacher you see. She played the introduction and my mouth - I must have been like a goldfish. Not a soun
d came out. She played the introduction three times and mother nearly came and took me off the stage. However the teacher started it. Singing. Well then I was all right, I could sing it to the end. But I couldn't begin. Oh I did suffer. The mouth would op
en but no sound came out. So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Only special days. Whitsuntide and Christmas and suchlike things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was there a temperance club associated with the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh the Band of Hope belonged to the chapel. Not the 
church. No. No, it's the chapel is the Band of Hope.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about being taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes, we had our little prayers at night. But probably they were gabbled but they were said. You know - my simplicity. And you thought about a four legged creature.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you ever have family prayers or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
No, we never had family prayers. One time the vicar said to dad - now then Jim - was your wife and Jack having a bit of 
trouble? On Sunday. I don't know, said dad, they very often do, why? And in those days you see the vicar took this class of bigger boys, and they used to have to learn the collect for the day and so - it was Jack's turn and he stood up and he said, Oh Lor
d
 we beseech thee, send my mother up a beech tree. And sat down. And Mr Wannock says, come along Jack, come along. There are more lines to the collect than that. Ah, but I haven't thought of any more. He never got the collect out of him. And he said he nev
er smiled. Dad said, probably his mother had got up his back. Some boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Now your parents political attitudes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Staunch Tories. Both of them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you know why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I expect their fathers were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you remember them voting in an election 
before 1919? The 1918 would be the first one that your mother would be able to vote at.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. Well she went to vote - a week before she died, in 1945. She had to be taken but she went. And she got very absent minded. And - it was down at the school and - and, yes, perhaps you'd better not put this in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Would she vote in the 1918 election do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 If mother had a vote she'd definitely use it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And it would be Conservative?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 In some places people used to feel they mig
ht risk losing their job or their house if they voted differently from their employers or anything like that, do you know if your father ever felt himself under any kind of pressure?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Never. Never. And he'd have walked the streets and still have been 
a Tory. He'd go out in the garden and the neighbour next door, Mr Dawson and his brother, another Mr Dawson, and another man all used to - and they were Labour. And Parliament would sit out there. Mother would say, oh Parliaments sitting. And all of a sud
den - you'd hear - pa's voice said, I forget bloody neighbours. Oh no, he never - he never kept quiet, not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was he actually a member of the Tory party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 He didn't work for the party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No. He didn't. His daughter has done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You yourself you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh rather, she's resigned from the Chairman's post of the Riddlesden branch - in January. And I was the Chairman for three years. Then I was the President three years before that and then I was the Chairman three years before that. 
And I just thought, right - younger blood can come forward. But I'm still on the committee. So to give me a little post of honour I am a Vice-Chairman. But I don't think the Vice-Chairman will do anything. Except sit at the top of the table at the Annual 
general.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your mother belong to the party at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh dear no, she voted - and that was quite enough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Did they take part in any political activity at all other than at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Only dad's Parliament in the garden you see. You 
see, where he had his notions. He was the only Tory. You see. And the words would run rather warm, you see. No fur coat was needed when the Parliament was sitting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their time?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 They n
ever had any. Mother had all her knitting. And her sewing, when I got bigger I took over the sewing you see but - she knitted - she used to knit me most beautiful two-ply jumpers. And as you know they take a bit of doing. And - she never had any idle time
.
 She always had something. And the tragedy was before she died during the war she knits socks, socks, socks. She nearly provided the whole Army with socks. Then she had one of her little attacks - and - she couldn't remember how to turn the heel. So she w
ent onto the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5060256\charrsid9796337 balacl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
ava helmets. Then she had another do and she couldn't remember the mitering at the sides. So she went on to scarves. And then the poor soul forgot how to wrap the wool over the needle. So she had to give it up. Oh she never had any - spar
e - oh, patience. Oh she played patience every day, every day after about - 1918. She'd have an hour with the patience cards. She wore the cards out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 But before 1918 it would be knitting and sewing and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 She never had any idle time. What w
ith her reading and her knitting and her sewing and her cooking and her - no, she was fully occupied.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did she not have any interests outside the home at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Only when she went down to a little concert in the school. And she'd go to town now and
 again for a bit of shopping. But she'd no sort of Women's - body or anything that - no, as I tell you she liked - if she had a spare hour she liked to get onto the - onto the book.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 About what time would your father get in from work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Five-ish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How many evenings in the week would he spend at home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - do you mean did he go to the pub and suchlike? No, he didn't because beer gave him lumbago. And he couldn't drink it. And he couldn't afford a lot of whisky. He'd go into his garden an
d potter about and potter about with his hens. And if it was summertime we used to have summer evenings in those days. You see, - where it was hot until bedtime. He'd have a chair outside. No, he wasn't a pub man at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was there any outside interest at all that he followed regularly or not?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Every Saturday night he went to town and he'd call on his friend Robert Pagett, the ironmonger, and - they'd go to the Albert and have this glass of whisky, you see. And then they'd have a good gossip and he would come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You say he never took part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no. No. He wouldn't know a cricket ball from a football. It was his shooting that he liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did he ever go to the races or put a bet on anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh - he'd put a bob on a h
orse, none of his pals would put a bob on the same horse. The stuffing all dropped out of dad's before it got there. Oh no, he wasn't a bit of good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 But he'd have a bash now and then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 He'd put a bob on now and again, when not one friend would ha
ve a bob on the same house. Because it never - never finished even. No, it was a well known fact that he was no good at all. He had a brother who used to buy all his wife's clothes and pay for the holidays and - everything, out of his winnings. Everything
. His wife used to say, oh this was Golden Wonder, or - this was - so and so and so and so you see. But - no, dad's always went down the drain, he wasn't a bit of good with those things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your father and mother belong to any savings clubs, for sickn
ess or funeral benefit or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh - he had to have a sick club. He had the same sick club that he had - when he was living at Casterton. But I don't know how it worked really, because those two years he was ill before he died, he only got two an
d six a week out of it. Well he paid more than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was there one that you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh Jack, yes. Oh yes, he was - me sister and I get on beautifully altho
ugh we're not a bit alike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. As my sister said, we suffer fools gladly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 As a child who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh we'd a lot of friends. We all had friends, the boys always had friends. I had a lot of friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Where would you play, would it be in the yard, the garden, the street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well you see when I was at the playing age it would be when were down at the Riddlesden cottage, that's it, and in the field behind, you know, the big old sycamore trees, and the 
roots are just above the garden - the ground. Well you see you could have doll's furniture and you can make a beautiful dolls house, on a fine day, have various rooms. All sorts of cubby holes, studies and what have you like, in these - oh we could have a
 beano in a tree root.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 When it was a wet day would you play in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Or in the wash house. It was a great big long narrow thing you see. Had a beano there, mother had the dolly legs you see. And it's - oh it must have been uncomfortable, we'
d sit on it as though it was a bike, and hold the front you see, and sort of work it somehow, went across. Oh it must have been uncomfortable. But you'd work it as it went across this thing. We got we could go beautifully. It was a lovely place to play in
.
 And mother could send us, we could make as much noise as we liked, because there was this back pantry affair before it reached her, and the passage. And - before it reached her, she could get on with her book beautifully. But - we could spend a whole aft
ernoon there and - didn't matter if the heavens fell in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What sort of games did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What sort of games? Do you mean table games? Like Ludo and tiddywinks and -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Or outdoor games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Outdoor, oh - oh outdoors. Oh I don't know, you cou
ld - it was at the day - days where you had a whip and top you know and hopscotch and - some other little things that you called checks. Oh before your day - those were. But - indoors well you'd have all these - card games and suchlike, when there's a lot
 of you you can have real good - beg o' my neighbours and all the rest of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What would happened if you got dirty, were you scolded or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - if you got dirty - you saw to it that you jolly well got clean before your mother found you. Don't you see? And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about torn clothes or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - I did get walloped one time, you know you had white petticoats - with embroidery on and this had little - daisies and one Sunday in church I picked all the daisies out of the front. My
 bottom was very red after that, and I had to spend the afternoon in bed, see. I deserved it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Were you free to play with anybody you pleased, or were there some children you weren't to play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Provided they hadn't nits in their hair. If they 
had nits in their hair you couldn't play with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 They were the only children you were discouraged from playing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
That was the only lot, yes. If mother saw a lot of this you know - it was time to come in. Because - I mean the boys could get them. You never hear of those things now do you. I don't know why.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you belong to any youth organizations other than the church ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No. We hadn't - oh - me, myself you mean? No. Hadn't time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How did you spend your free time when you 
were at school, did you have any hobbies like keeping pets or collecting things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well you see - Isaac was - poorly at the time. Now he had all his little things, he'd silk worms and those things, well he couldn't clean them out when he was flat on hi
s back. So - it was a busy time keeping his silk worms - and he had his great big ugly - ugh - spiders. Ugh. They were to clean out, and he'd have this, that and the other. Well they were all to keep clean you see. So I can't remember having any - time to
 fritter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you go for walks and go bicycling at all, fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh we never had a bike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 But you went for walks?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes, we might - we could go on a picnic you see. Mother had a copper kettle, a little one. How she dare let us take it I 
don't know. And - a little sort of - meth. thing I remember right, I can remember taking this methylated in a bottle. And she let us. Ten years old she let us do it. We would go to Gill Grange you see, light the meth. And fill this - copper kettle, and sh
e
 would put us a bit of tea in and a little muslin bag with a - a cotton to it see. When it boiled drop it in, of course I don't suppose it ever boiled. I don't suppose it ever did. And then we'd have our sandwiches. And Gill Grange, it's away over - that 
w
ay you know, it's beyond - Robin High of Silsden. And there's a very beautiful waterfall. Well you see, on a lovely day you could go and paddle and even if it wasn't a lovely day you had to paddle if your legs were blue. And - oh yes, we'd these beautiful
 
picnic. Fishing. Well our fishing was done in the canal. And the boys would catch - what they called a roach, about so big. And I've seen my mother if they only caught one, clean it and cook it for them. One. Wasn't worth dirtying the pan for was it. But 
she would do it because they'd caught it and they wanted the fish at teatime. Much better if they caught two or three but if there was only one she would do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And it was in the canal where you learnt to swim?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes, yes, there wasn't anywhere else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you learn to swim properly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
No, because I didn't like it. I - I was Canute. That's what Jack used to say, hello, Canute's coming. Put her foot in and draw back. Oh no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you take part in any sports at all yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Not when I was very little, because there weren't any you see. Only the racing on Whit Monday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 As a child did you ever go to a theatre or a concert or music hall or cinema?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well you didn't go to the theatre. Our concerts were in the school. See
 you couldn't get to Keighley, it was too far. And the first time we went to the - pictures, it was when the Cavendish Street opened, that was the only one. And mother took three of us. Oh it was the street, it must have been in the summer holidays or som
e
 holiday. She took us and of course the commissionaire at the door said, where would you like to sit missus? You can have front row. So mother thought it was real having front row. Right. And so she piloted we three - to my dying day do you know it was a 
desert scene, I shall see these camels nearly coming onto my face. And so that was my first experience of going to the pictures. And it was mother's first and she never forgot it. Oh, she says -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You never went on the front row again?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Never. If s
he was going to Keighley I'd say, well - go in the afternoon mother, there's a good historical picture, you know, Mary Queen of Scots or something like that on at the Regent, go there. Yes, she says, and I'll sit on front row. So - no, you - you couldn't 
go to theatres and things. Not from here. Besides if one had gone the lot would have gone. Oh - couldn't be done. Couldn't be done at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your parents give you any pocket money as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes, we had a ha'penny a week each. And if we were v
ery good and had done - an extra amount of jobs it might be a penny. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How did you spend your money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh - well - we weren't all of the same mind you see. Jack could be very very spendthrift. Well maybe he wanted to borrow a ha'penny now a
nd again off me. So I had to keep a bit of reserve to let him have it. See it wouldn't have done if I hadn't. Would it? Oh no, no. No, and then you see we had to save up for this - famous summer holiday, it took us all the year to save it up. Oh yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you have any to spend on sweets or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh mother used to buy four ounces of mint imperials which she used to call bachelors buttons. And she bought a quarter a week with the groceries you see. And then she would make a big pan of 
toffee. And there was the little pan of toffee which Isaac made on the Saturday night. So we really had plenty you see. But - I know - you had to be very careful you see. And you - it was amazing how you could save these ha'pennies. And the odd times if y
ou got a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after the house or the family ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Do you mean financially or - well, you see, mother had come - a stranger in a strange land.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What would happen if she was ill, or do you 
not remember her being ill when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well we had a nice neighbour, Mrs Peeling. There were the two cottages together you see. I can remember that she popped in now and again, and Mrs Peeling you see would make our dinner, so mother must have been out of salts. Mustn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you remember what happened when one of the younger children was born?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
I think our grandmother came. I have a feeling she did. She would come and she would be there a few weeks you see. So it would be then wouldn't it, at the birth.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
You didn't have any relatives living near, what about friends? Did your parents have friends, you've already mentioned your father's friends, what about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Mother wasn't a person - who - made a bosom friend,
 not a mate. She was sort of nice to anybody. But she wasn't the matey type. 'Cos her books you see. Were her friends. Be careful. Just be careful, don't - don't - sort of marry yourself too much to your books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were friends invited into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Their friends? Anybody who came was made welcome.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did they come casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Rather than by invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. Pop in, have a walk on Sundays or Saturdays you know and pop in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And they'd be offered something, whatever was going?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. And if there was nothing to go, well they didn't get it. See? You can't keep a full pantry with five kids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And there wasn't much neighbouring?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no, mother wasn't a neighbourer. If anybody was poorly - and they were in a bit of a j
am mother would go. But she wouldn't go - she'd do what she had to do - and I know there was a lady up on the top, oh I was only about fifteen, and she was having a baby and the midwife hadn't arrived and - the husband, I can remember him coming down here
 
in a real tizzy about ten o'clock. This baby was on the way and there was nobody there and the doctor he couldn't get hold of him, would mother go. Well mother came back next morning to get dad's breakfast, but she never went in that house again. And she'
d never been in it before. But she was friendly you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
When your parents were with their friends what sort of things did they do, was it conversation or games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Conversation and if it was - if it wanted vetting we kids were sent out to play. Don't you see? Little pigs have big ears.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Did you think of some people belonging to one social class and some to another before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you mean snobs?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Different stratus of society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well, I'm afraid - we all thought ourselves as good a
s our neighbours. That's what it was. We didn't consider anybody - on a higher plane than we were. Money yes, but - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from another, this matter of curtseying for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh - oh yes, but that was at titles you see. But - we were always taught - to treat people with respect whether they were rich or poor. That's it, always. And I think that lives, you know, throughout life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was there anybody that you called sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well you're supposed to say sir to the doctor. And - but we didn't. Mother would. But - I'm afraid we kids didn't. And we were supposed to say sir to the vicar. But behind his back we used to call him chummy. Yes and his wife was Cherry Blossom
. And they lived here twenty-six years so it couldn't have been a bad little parish could it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 But you rebelled against this idea of showing respect by curtseying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. It - we weren't born in that age. And we - I couldn't go back to that age you
 see. No, I didn't like it. I thought why should I? We're doing something for her. And for the Countess of Bective you see well I had to pull the tackings out for her. She couldn't go about with the tacking threads in, why should I say it. I shouldn't say
 m'lady. I shouldn't curtsey, and I wouldn't. And I expect at the back of the old lady's mind she would say good for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 She never showed any resentment because you didn't?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh no, she'd give me a little pat on the head.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 In Riddlesden who were considered to be the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
The vicar. Schoolmaster. He'd about eight children. So they had to struggle on as we had. I think the schoolmaster in those days got two pounds a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was it because of their position that they wer
e considered important, or for any other reason?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
No, I think he was the vicar of the parish and he was the schoolmaster, and the schoolmaster's children and the Thorn borough children you see and that was us, we all sort of batted together you see, i
f - if there were any of the Smith's missing, oh they'll be at Thorn borough\rquote s you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Was there free and easy mixing amongst the different members of the community like the schoolmaster and the clergy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well it was a little tiny village you se
e. And it was only - when the building started and people came from the town. You see when this was rural - the rates were very very much lighter than they were in Keighbley. So people would come up here, to avoid the heavy rates. And - that was when snob
bery started. You see - everybody was the same. Before. It was only when - when the influx from the town - that's a good word isn't it - for Tuesday teatime - would come and - well we got a few snobs, and we still have a few snobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 But in those days not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh no, no, no. It was a friendly little village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
What would you say was the difference if any between the sort of people who went to the C. of E. and the people who went to the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well you see - the chapel people were better.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 In what way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh they'd a better chance of getting - getting to heaven than we Anglicans. Do you go to chapel? Oh no. The - the Methodists were - much nearer heaven than the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5060256\charrsid9796337 
Anglicans}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 . Therefore it didn't quite matter what you did at church you see. Y
ou couldn't fall from grace because you weren't there. Oh no, the Methodists were much better than we.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Would you say that most people round and about had the same standard of living or were there different standards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well of course you see - wit
h being a big family - in those days a big family hadn't a lot of money, therefore you hadn't a high standard of living. And my parents - believed - in - good food and a happy home - rather than achieving to - buying a bit of brass or something for the ho
use you know. Than worldly goods. I fancy when I look back - they had the idea that their - that what they gave to the children was much better than giving worldly goods.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Would there be some families who would emphasise the worldly goods?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well, a
 lot of families - they might have taties and salt, you see, and - have a bit finer home. Well my mother didn't believe in that, she believed in a good solid meal. I know a lot of my friends, their homes were much smarter than ours was. But - when it got 
down - I used to grumble sometimes, say oh so and so, Sara Moss's mother you know, they've got so and so and so and so. She says, and what has she had for her dinner? She'd say that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you think that either type felt itself superior to the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I don't really think we bothered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well of course there were - and there are today you know, rough families. There's one down the road, don't know whether it's next door. I thin
k if children are brought up - to be decent and one thing and another in the home it's naturally ingrained in you isn't it. You might have an odd burst now and again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was there any distinction felt between craftsmen and labourers do you think?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 There might have been.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You say the labourers got more money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well you see they could start - they could start labouring, whereas - a young man - had to go and learn a trade and he would only get - a few shillings a week. As Rene Higgins was sayin
g on Saturday, when she started at the mill at six o'clock in the morning and worked until twelve when she was twelve years old, she got a shilling for that week. Well that was sweated labour wasn't it. And that was learning the spinning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you think
 your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social group or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No she didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Do you remember anybody being described as a real gentleman or a real lady round about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I - I used to - to hear mother describe somebody and I couldn
't understand it because I was only very young at the time, as one of nature's gentlemen. I didn't know what she meant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you know the person concerned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. It was somebody who died. And I was always very fond of him, he once gave me sixpence and it was untold wealth. And when he died mother said he was one of nature's gentlemen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you know why she had that feeling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No. No. I've no idea. But - I got this sixpence.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you remember seeing a policeman around in Riddlesden when y
ou were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well you see - the policeman, they called him Atkinson, and he was a friend of dad's, so he'd come to the house, we never had any fear of him. He'd just simply come and - he might call and have a cup of tea in the morning or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - I could sit on his knee and that's what I couldn't today if he'd been alive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your mother ever say she'd call a policeman if you were naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well it was no good. No, no, it wouldn't have made a bit of difference.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How do you think he treated the people in general?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well you see if you're about nine years old it's difficult, if a person is nice to you you naturally think he's nice - to the whole world.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was your cottage a rented home or did it belong to your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I think it would go in with the wages wouldn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you see anything of the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
We all played together. His eldest son nursed me when I was three weeks old. He'd gone on a fishing expedi
tion to Casterton you see and - I fancy it would be all in the air, that they would gradually persuade dad to come over here you know. And - his eldest son nursed me when - of course if I - when he was in practice in the town as a solicitor if I wanted to
 
make a will he never charged me. His son does mind you. Yes. Yes, I have to pay now when I want to make a will. But - oh I - I could make a fresh will every year when Mr Alfred was alive. I got away with it beautifully. You never thought that - his son ch
arges me the guinea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
You had the feeling that your parents did have to struggle to make needs meet did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 They would have to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you feel it though at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh dear no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 So you wouldn't have any particular views about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
No. We'd plenty to eat, we'd a comfortable bed, we'd clothes to wear, we were happy. And a ha'penny a week. To do as you wanted with. No - it was never a case - oh, there's sixpence, go and get some sweets. Nothing like that you know. Because the ba
chelors buttons - well they were probably four ounces for threepence ha'penny in those days you see. But mother bought those for the family. After that she would make toffee.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your parents ever have to have financial help from any source?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I never heard of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
As a child how often during the week would you have meat, was it fairly frequently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
How often we had meat? Well you see my mother was most marvellous cook. She could buy sheep\rquote s head. She could cook it, and make beautiful pott
ed meat from the cheeks and all the rest of it you see, and then soup from the other part. Well if children have a big bowl of soup with vegetables and dumplings in they have no room for - for meat. And this beautiful potted meat. Well that would go in th
e
 bottom of a shepherds pie wouldn't it for another day. There you are. There would always be - meat of some sort. Practically every day. One meal we used to thoroughly enjoy was a huge macaroni cheese. Well if you got your tummies full of macaroni cheese 
followed by apple pasty - you hadn't room to turn round. No, I don't think you need bother as to - calories, proteins or anything. They weren't alive in those days. But mother saw to it that the meals were filling, and good. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your mother or your father actually make a show of affection for you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh mother never did. You see, she wouldn't have wanted us to get - what is now known as swelled headed. She might have been proud of any achievement underneath but she wouldn't have shown it. Da
d would probably say - eeh girls, I don't know whatever I would do without you. Well mother wouldn't have done. You see. Probably it was underneath and she felt it, but - she wouldn't want us to get big headed. See? Just the different type of person. And 
we never expected it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Your father went to the pub occasionally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no, he didn't. He never went to the pub. He couldn't drink beer because it gave him lumbago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I thought you told me he went to the Albert?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh to the Albert in the town o
n Saturday nights with his friend. For one whisky.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about your mother, did she ever go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
I told you she was once drunk with nettle beer. Mother would never be inside a pub in her life I don't suppose. They didn't in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Can you 
remember anybody in Riddlesden who moved up in the world or down in the world when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes, quite a lot of people, but it - wouldn't do to say. Because they might simply say, well it's jealousy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You mean people who moved up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. We who didn't move - so much you see, weren't in what we call the money, they might say it was jealousy on our part you see, so it wouldn't do to say would it. Well, you see, in an industrial area - it's a good old saying, where there's much there's 
money isn't it. And - well industry - what would you say it revolves - they have some marvelous times in it haven't they, and in textile. Other times they can have very grim ones. So - if there's a lot of money made at the time - some - some of my friends
 
are extremely well off. But everybody - in the whole area is working class. A man down the lane, not - opposite - the other side of the road to the - Harringtons, higher up, he died a double barrelled millionaire. But he termed himself working class. It m
a
de his money. Yes. No, his mother was - well she darned his socks and darned his socks and - I don't know how he walked on them, she put so many darns under the heel. But - that was just it. She once reprimanded me when I was sewing. She wore a little mod
e
sty vest you see in her dress, and I'd had something to do at one of her dresses. And this thing, it was lace and it had little darns in it and holes. So - I just took it out - oh I had to put a new vest in. Threw it on the fire. You see. My mother wouldn
'
t have looked at it. So her daughter-in-law came the following day. She said, granny wants her vest. She said, I don't know what she means by her vest, but she wants the vest. So - I said, I burnt it. What? I said, it was all holes and darns. Well she say
s
, you'd better go and tell her then, I daren't. And yet her son could buy her a Rolls Royce for her seventieth birthday. You see, that's how the - moneyed people are up here. So I had to tell granny - that - I'd burnt the vest. Well, she said, you'd no bu
siness. But I said, it was full of holes and darns. Well, she said, it would have done for morning. You'll never die wealthy, never. And I'm sure I don't want if that was how you got to be. But - no, everybody - in Keighley I consider working class.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 When your father was alive, prior to 1918, was he ever ill and off work?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well he'd get his lumbago. It was called lumbago in those days. Perhaps now it would be muscular rheumatism you see. But - that's about all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you know whether his wage was affected if he was off ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
It wasn't, not for a week or two. It might if he'd been away a long period, it probably would have been. But not for a short period.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And you don't remember a long period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I never remember him being off a long p
eriod, except the last two years before he died you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Were you given lessons at all by your parents or anybody before you went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How old were you when you first started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What was the length of the school day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Nine o'clock in the morning and we finished at four in the afternoon. We'd have the midday, I don't know whether it was an hour or an hour and a half. An hour and a half probably.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What sort of a school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 It was a Church of England school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes. Yes, very. The standards went up to - standard seven and ex-seven. We all got into the ex-seventh. Mother said it was because the schoolmaster was fed up of us in the other. It wasn't that our ability was there you see. So
 you can tell she didn't want us to become swelled headed. If we went boasting home said we were in ex-seven, oh, she said, it's only because Mr Smith's fed up with you in the lower classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How did you get to school, was it a long way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well - it would take us quarter of an hour to walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you go alone or did somebody go with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well there was always a squad you see. There was a little hamlet beyond Riddlesden cottages, Highcote, it's all built up now with modern houses. But there 
were about - six or seven houses there, well - those children all came along to school you see and then - there was our five eventually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh we thought it was great. We really thought it was great. All the family did. I - I think we must have been rather precocious because - the schoolmaster once told dad he could do with some weights to keep us down. See?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh I think we liked them all. Yes, I think so. The vicar used to
 go three mornings a week to take half an hour's scripture lesson. And - we quite enjoyed that. I think on the whole school was a very pleasant place to do to. There are all these school dinners now, well when the weather was very bad mother used to pack 
t
he sandwiches you see. And if she hadn't bread left to - if it was the day before the baking day and the bread was done, dad used to arrive at school at twelve o'clock with - perhaps a big shepherds pie or something like that for us all. You see. Oh he di
d
 all those tricks for - his flock. But - no, I think on the whole school was very very pleasant. We had these little concerts you see, with being a Church of England school it sort of had to support itself pretty well, and you had to have the concerts eve
r
y now and again - and then Mrs Clarkson down at Riddlesden Hall used to give prizes once a year for needlework. Two for the sewing and two for the knitting. So - no, it was very very pleasant was the school. And I think we did very well to pack in - in wh
a
t - eight years - what has had to - support us all our life, don't you think so? I think so. Probably - apart from science and things like that, we knew - we had a better grounding than the children of today have. But I think the spelling of some of the c
h
ildren - well the youngster who used to live next door, she'd bring her homework in sometimes and the spelling was deplorable. And of course I loathe a badly spelt word. And she was fifteen. But it was just dreadful that - the way she spelt things. Oh we 
w
ould have go our knuckles rapped, if we had made a mistake. And if mother had caught us making a mistake in the grammar we'd have got more than the knuckles rapped. She'd say, what do you think I send you to school for? Gosh - with her - great love of rea
ding you see she could correct her - flock couldn't she.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did the teachers emphasise such things as manners and tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes, we had to have a - an inspection every morning, to see if our shoes were clean you see, and polished. But my brother 
Jack, if he'd been busy he put both his feet together and took the blacking brush over you see like that and polished. So the schoolmaster got wise, he'd say, open your feet Jack. Well he hadn't done the insides you see, he'd just done the visible part. O
h yes, you had inspections like that. You had to be very particular about hanging - your coats up with the hanger. Well - over the pegs they go now don't they, it doesn't matter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh my word, you had to be in school when th
e bell rang. We hadn't to be a second late unless you had a note from your parents. No trailing in at quarter past nine as they do today.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - that is what I always say, the manner of a child - in her speaking or his speaking, depends upon the home life. You see. We hadn't {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Yorkshire{\*\xmlclose}
 parents. And we'd parents who - from habit I suppose spoke perfect English. Therefore we never thought of sidestepping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about the other children in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh there'
d be a bit of thee-ing and thou-ing you see. And - nowt o'sort style of a thing, but - we would never have thought of that. But that's the home life isn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What line did the teachers take on that, did they try to correct it or not?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you kno
w, I can't remember so far back. You see, I would be one of them. Had I been - a pupil teacher which they used to have in those days it would have been different. But just being one of the crowd - I couldn't - I would never notice if they corrected it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well, Mr Smith used to have a black ruler, a round one you see about so long. The lads used to get that. And the girls had to go out and stand and face the class. And not to laugh 
while they were - be much easier if you'd had to face the blackboard. But that was the punishment that was meted out to the girls. But the boys, if they were very very naughty - but it wasn't often, I think Mr Smith - gave his own boys - more cane than an
y
body else. There wasn't a lot of caning in school, very little. One teacher had a switch. But it wasn't used very - never on the girls that I can remember. Although I daresay the girls needed it more than boys. But our punishment was to stand and face the
 class, with a straight face.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
If the boys did something which didn't merit caning did they have that sort of thing? Was there a lesser punishment for the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
I suppose there would be but you see - you just take it as part and parcel don't you. You never think of what - fifty odd years repeating it all. If I had known over fifty years ago that I would be memorizing it I would have taken a bit more trouble.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Your mother showed some interest in your work at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about your father, did he also?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well - yes. He didn't dictate to us like mother did you see but - he liked to be told and kept up to date with all our - activities and learning and all therest of it. He was a good father.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What from did your mother's interest take?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well in the spelling I suppose. And the punctuation and the grammar and - all things like that. It irritated her - if we made mistakes, therefore we daren't make mistakes. Because as I have told you, mother had a heavy hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did they ask you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
In all probability we would tell it without being asked. Wouldn't we? We'd go bursting in. Not like the kids today - some of them if you - well if I said to the youngster next door, what have you been doing? Oh - 
the same old thing. You know. We're not like that, we would go bursting in, we've been doing so and so, we've been doing map drawing. Map drawing was my favourite. I loved to go round the coast of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Africa{\*\xmlclose}
 you know. Oh simply loved it. But - that suited me very very nicely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Your parents knew the schoolmaster, did they know the other teachers, did they meet them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Everybody knew everybody. There was an infants mistress, Mrs Waddington, she used to live down at the bottom of this street. And - she was
 a motherly sort you know and - the schoolmaster's daughter was one of the teachers. Everybody knew everybody in the village because it was so small.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you think your parents discussed your schoolwork with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Probably. I daresay they would d
o you see. But no - teacher parents association as there is today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Would your parents visit the school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes, if there was an exhibition of our work you know, our - needlework and suchlike, the mother's went. Then we always had this concert at the Christmas, to make - extra money. Well the parents always went to that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Did the other children come from similar types of home to yours or from a variety?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well I should say we were all very similar. One or two perhaps had a bit more 
money. And one girl never wore a pinafore, you see we wore pinafores with - frills, beautifully goffered frills round the shoulders. You know. Well this other girl didn't, she used to wear a navy blouse with stripes on, a sailor collar you see. So when sh
e spilt the ink down the skirt and spoilt it we all laughed. Would only have bone on our pinafores but you see - she was very disdainful - of - but she hasn't prospered any better.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from
 the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Being one of the class I wouldn't know. I wouldn't know that you see. The schoolmaster never favoured his own. If he lost his temper one of his own got the walloping. I expect he dared do it to them you see without any - after effects.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Gangs of groups. Oh you'd have your little pally groups you know. And spiteful groups, oh don't speak to her, she said so and so, you know, just as there are today. I don't think that side has altered at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were some children left out of things altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well if they were it was their own fault. Don't you think so? I think if - everybody that - had a bit of - pep about them, you know, were included with everything. I expect we were - a b
it catty you know and - we wouldn't have the very very shy people with us. Don't think it ever bothered our family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you stay at this school until you were thirteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And that was when you left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 That was the completion of my education.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Would you have stayed on at school longer if you could have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
You couldn't stay at this school any longer. Unless you were a bit dunce. And - as we all reached the standard ex-seven you see, well you couldn't go any further. And the
 next thing after that you had to win a scholarship for the grammar school. And - apart from winning the scholarship it would cost your parents quite a lot. Well our parents couldn't afford it for five children. So we each one had to - make our own way an
d use our own ability.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Would there have been any facilities for part time evening classes or anything like that in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well, the boys all went to evening classes, the two elder boys went for shorthand and typing. But you see when I starte
d work in the town, my sister started. Shops were open from eight in the morning 'til eight in the evening. Well you couldn't go to evening classes then. You were jolly glad to come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you have any regrets about this, about your education?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
I don't think so. I think I get by pretty well. A little spattering of - other languages and all the rest of it. My sister's had a marvellous job. She could look at a thousand pound and just run up it and run down it, put the total. Bot's your uncle. And
 she left school when she was thirteen. No, I - I don't think we had any regrets. They boys went to the evening classes for a shorthand. But apart from that - well the order of the day was you go to work so we went to work. After I'd - I'd had my two year
s up at Kirkby Lonsdale.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 That was from the age of thirteen you then went to Kirkby Lonsdale?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes, for two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
While you were still at school did you ever have any little part time job to earn a little money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What we used to run mess
ages for a neighbour and - there was a Co-op at the bottom of this street, and we'd come for her shopping. It was a - much easier to give us a penny you see. But a penny was all we got and a biscuit. Children in those days didn't do part jobs as they do t
oday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Your first experience of work then was when you went to Kirkby Lonsdale?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well it - it wasn't learning dressmaking and that was the - idea that I went with you see, it was being the little mug for these two maiden aunts, so that they could get on with their sewing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Who's idea was it that you went there, was it your mother's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well, it was an arrangement that had been going on for years I think. Mother thought it would be very nice if I learnt dressmaking. They thought it would be ve
ry nice if I went to them. When I got there you know I had the doorsteps to keep clean and - a real little mug. Cheap labour. I would never make a sewer, never. So mother brought me home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 While you were at Kirkby Lonsdale what hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well it just depended what time you - had to get up, sometimes we would get up about eight. Sometimes we would get up at six. Just depended what they wanted to do you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You didn't have stipulated hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh dear, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you work on Saturdays or Sundays?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. Yes. You did just whatever there was. It wasn't really a happy - two years. Only I hadn't the commonsense to write home and tell dad and mother you see. I didn't quite know what the - idea would be if I did, but - when I
 did tell them what I had to do, well why didn't you say before? Well a child of thirteen in those days hadn't quite as much up as one of thirteen now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you ever have any holiday while you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Only to come back home for a week whilst they took a weeks holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What were the arrangements about paying you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I didn't have any pay. I might get sixpence now and again. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I resented it. Just - of course there was nothing to spend it on t
here you see. I think I got half a crown when I came home for the week. That was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I suppose you would have your keep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes. They kept me you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your mother expect you to give any of your earnings to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 She thought I was gett
ing paid. Don't you see? Whereas I wasn't. Oh no, we must forget about that. It was a wasted two years, except that it - sort of educated me NOT to trust relatives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Was it while you were working with your aunts that you came into contact with these titled customers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes, yes. Yes, they had a very very - good clientele. Very good. But - I was just the mug. Eeh dear. Probably it didn't do me any harm in the long run.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 At about fifteen then you came home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I came back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What happened then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well I went to this lady who lived down the road there. She was busy. Just for the summer season you see, to see how much or how little I knew. Whether I should go on with the idea of sewing or whether I should branch out in another direction.
 And she said continue. Well when she - her business slackened off in the Autumn you see. I went to work at a shop in the town - and I was there until 1918. So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
This first short time with this lady, was that a sort of apprenticeship or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I 
got five shillings a week. So it wouldn't really be an apprenticeship would it. Because when my sister went as a millinery apprentice she got half a crown a week for eighteen months. So it was a little more than an apprenticeship at five shillings a week 
wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Do you consider that you served an apprenticeship in the real sense at all?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
I never actually served an apprenticeship. Never. But I like to think that I've done good work since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You acquired the skill yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Evidently.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What were you doing in your first job here, the short term?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well, doing anything I could do help the lady.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 But it would be sewing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes, it was all sewing. Everything, yes, we were never out of the workroom. And then - when I went to work at this shop on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}North Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, that was - really a very high class place, you know. Before your days blouses used to have collars of tiny trellis bands. You know, it was all trellis - and the fronts would be trellised. Well we did all that kind of work
. No good to the eyes at all. But - most beautiful work it used to be. Mrs Wilson, the head, was an absolute artist. And her blouses were famed you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were these made to customer's orders?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was all the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well we used to 
- it was so seldom we had spare time. If we had a bit of spare time we might make one or two for stock. But - we very seldom had them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What did your working day consist of when you got into a proper job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Eight o'clock in the morning until eight 
o'clock at night. Then when the first world war was on - we used to finish at seven, you see, because there was a black-out, but still that was a good long day you see, we always started at eight. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What breaks did you have?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well I used to 
come home in the middle of the day. I had an hour and a half. Otherwise it meant taking sandwiches which did not agree with me. And we - the tram only brought us to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Erworth Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} you know. Not to the bridge. Nearer Keighley than the bridge and we - had to w
alk up. Was a good stiff walk to do it in quarter of an hour. Twenty minutes as a rule. And mother would have the dinner just ready. And Jack and I used to come home on the same tram. And then we would go back and catch the twenty minutes past one tram. A
nd - be back in work at half past. You had to scoot along {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}North Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 to be in at half past. You couldn't stop and say little - pleasant things as you went along you know, but - we were very very grateful - when we could finish at seven in the evening. 'Co
s if you had a boyfriend waiting you could go to the pictures. You see, on the Saturday night. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You worked 'til seven on Saturdays did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh yes. Tuesday was the half day. But woe betide us if we were late in the morning. Quarter of an ho
ur late - right, you make it up. It wasn't taken off the wages, you make it up. Well if you were one or two mornings a bit late, that meant you had about an hour to make up. And if we were very busy we had to work over on the Tuesday afternoon until four 
o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 When you were working through 'til eight did you have a tea break?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 A half an hour. And that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
What did you feel about the work when you did get into the sewing job proper, did you like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh I loved it. I just l
oved it. I was very happy doing it. Unfortunately the shop finished in 1918 and at the same time mother developed rheumatic fever so I would have had to stay at home whether or not. And she was a bit of a care ever after. So - it all fitted in. Oh I loved
 the working hours. I liked the type of work you know, the dinner the better. Chiffons were very fashionable then. I loved working with chiffons. Oh I don't know, I would have hated a lot of these rayon - nylon things that are going now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How did you get on with the other people you were working with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 With the other girls? We all got on beautifully.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 With the employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
I must have got on all right. Because - she went to live at St Annes and up to her dying I used to go every February - and spend a week with her. So I must have - oh I must have got on all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Would you have preferred any other type of occupation if you'd had a free choice?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes, I would have liked to have gone nursing. I wanted to do in the first world war but
 mother said, No. The boys are leaving home, you stay. And if ma said stay you stayed. You see. 'Course you could understand it in a way. But that was the only thing I would have wanted to do. Now my sister had to learn - millinery. Which she did. And as 
soon as she was old enough to stand on her own two feet she put it all behind her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you at any time belong to a trade union or anything of that sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I don't think there were such things. I never heard of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you feel that your empl
oyer and the workers had the same outlook towards the work or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
To tell you the truth I don't think it ever entered our heads to criticize. Don't think so. We went to do the job, we enjoyed doing it and we were paid to do it. So I don't suppose - that it entered our heads to think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you feel that there were differences of interest amongst the workers?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 There were only what - one, two, three, four, five of us - in the workroom.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 So people say there's this big division between traine
d workers and others, did you feel that in your work or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh we were all trained to do that type of work otherwise - we'd have made a mess of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 There wasn't anybody who was more as labouring type of girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh no, no, no, no. You had to be very efficient or you were no use at all.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And you did all your own clearing up after yourselves and everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes. I used to hate doing the bottoms of cuffs. Well if there was a rush job you see and somebody else had to help you - Mrs Wils
on would say, now you have to have a bit of help with that job. It has to be finished by so and so. I suppose you will have left the bottom of the cuffs, haven't you? Yes, Mrs Wilson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Would you say that starting work changed your attitude to life or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I don't think so. No, I don't think so at all. Just went blithely on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 In your first job, was it in Riddlesden or in Keighley?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
The one where - that I worked for two or three months was just down the road here. And the next was in Keighley.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And you were paid five shillings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Down here I was paid five shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you feel that that was a fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well I don't think it was very bad you see, I had no tram fares. And it was a sort of trying me out to see whether I was - worth continuing with sewing or not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 I probably gave her the lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Would she give you something back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 She'd give me some pocket money. Might be a shilling a week, I don't know. 
I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And your wage would go into the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 It was just simply go in. You did in those days you see, you just handed it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
What about when you got to Keighley, to the shop? Did your wage increase there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh yes. Yes. I think it rose to twenty-three shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was that a case of making your wage there or was it a weekly amount?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh it was the weekly wage. You were paid by the week not by the work you did you see. Yes, it was twenty-three shillings which was a very good wage in those days. Very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you continue giving the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes, yes, I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you ever have any holidays there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Yes, we always had the yearly - what is called Parish Feast Holiday. You see, the last week in July. Then we have the Easter and the Whit and the Christmas. Monday and Tuesday when the shops were all closed. We'd have those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Were these paid or unpaid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Do you know, I can't remember. We wouldn't get paid for the week. Definitely. Because t
here was no sort of work or play. No, we would lose a weeks wage in the - summer holiday but - I can't remember about the Tuesday and - no, we wouldn't be paid for the Monday and Tuesday - for Easter and Whit. No, we'd have to lose that. It' a long time a
go.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 How did you feel that your employer at the shop treated you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well you didn't feel anything. You didn't feel any resentment at all because it was the way of life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You stayed at home from 1918 when your mother started to be ill, but you d
id some ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well I looked after her for a month or two and then - my pocket was getting empty you see and - people wanted me to do a bit of sewing, and I just started doing a bit. Every time I thought I'd go back into the world and take a job, which
 would have been much much more interesting - well mother would fall poorly again. So it just got that I was at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 And you stayed at home all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 When you started work did it change your relationship with your parents any?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Or with your brothers and sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Oh dear no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Did you continue to spend your Sunday in the same way, going to church and Sunday school
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Well of course you see you rose to be a Sunday school teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 So you carried on pretty much as before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Was it about this time after you left school that you began to take an interest in politics, or did that not come until later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh no, no, that didn't come until I became a widow. You see, helped to fill in a gap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 When you were in your teens did you show any interest at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 In other things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 In politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No, because you see - the women didn't have votes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What about your spare time, you hadn't got very much had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 No. Very little dear. Very little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you go out in the evenings at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well it just depended if you had a current boyfriend. And - I - when you have two brothers at home older than yourself, you have a lot of boyfriends. Because their friends come to the house yo
u see. You're no short of friends of the opposite sex. Life can be glorious, see. You were friendly with a whole lot without being desperately in love.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you make any special friends about that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 You mean - do you mean was I courting? Well
 perhaps about 1916 - I was - and the boy went to the war and he was killed in 1917. Well - I'm still very friendly with his sister. And his sister's daughter is my god daughter so - that doesn't speak so badly does it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What did you do with your frien
ds, was there any particular place you'd go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Well there was only about the pictures. That you could go to. Which was sixpence. You see. You got a beautiful seat for sixpence. Plush tip-ups. And - then you could go to the temperance hall - every - 
every Monday evening the Glee Union, males you know, used to give a concert in the Temperance Hall, which was sixpence. Well it was a glorious all male concert. In due time - many many years after, I married the conductor of the Glee Union. Not that me go
ing to the sixpenny concerts led up to it. Only his wife was alive and kicking in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your parents meet your friends, meet all your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
Oh they all came home. Everyone of them, it was open house for all friends to come to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did your parents expect to know where you were if you went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
They expected to know when you came back where you'd been. Which is vastly different. Isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Did you have to be home by a specified time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Yes, but you didn't always get ther
e. My sister was braver than I was. If she had to be in at ten and it was more convenient to be in at ten thirty she arrived at ten thirty. Where I would have come busting up the hill you know. Phew, puffed to bits to be in by ten, but not my sister.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 What would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 She just didn't care.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6186291 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 Was she reprimanded?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7881673 FH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13064976\charrsid9796337 
She'd be reprimanded and told what would happen if she did it again. Right mother, let me know when you've finished blowing your top. So there you go you see, just - two different natures.
\par }}